{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_goosefoot_ver01/data/sn84036285/00340581829/1930111301/0766.xml":{"full_text":"CHERRY SPRINGS\n(Special Correspondence)\nMiss Ruth Russell visited last\nSaturday with her brother Ned.\nMr. and Mrs. Ed. Milbar of Bill\nings were callers in this vicinity\nSaturday. Mrs. Milbar will be re\nmembered here as Viola Stinson.\nA large crowd attended the dance\nat the Thos. Saysell home Satur\nday night.\nMr. and Mrs. H. P. Hansen were\ncounty seat visitors Wednesday.\nMrs. Harry Clark and Lee Clark\nmotored to Red Lodge Wednesday.\nMr, and Mrs. Claude Chenowith\nand daughters Jean and Ruth of\nBridger were guests at the Ed.\nHansen home Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. W. B. Thomson\nand daughter Vivian olf Powell,\nWyoming called at the C. V. Clark\nhome Sunday.\nMrs. Joe Rooney and daughter\naind Mrs. Teddy Schrumpf and\ndaughter visited Thursday at the\nWiekierak home.\nMiss Rhoda Durst spent the\nweek end at her home in Red\nLodge.\nMiss Mary Obert spent Friday\nnight at the C. A. dels home.\nMrs. Herman De Vries called at\nthe Mike Sekora home Thursday.\nThere will be a dance at Cherry\nSprings Saturday, November 13.\nMr. and Mrs. Joe Obert, Sr. spent\nthe past week at the J. F. Hatten\nhome in Joliet.\nC. C, Pierce of Bridger spent\nThursday at the Ned Russell home.\nMiss Mary Hampton spent the\nWeek end at the W. Race home.\nMiss Edna Gaston of Roberts\nvisited at the C. A. Olels home\nThursday.\nMrs. S. W. Waples and children,\nMrs. Doty and children of Red\nLodge and Mrs. T. C. Schrumpf\nand children visited at the T. R.\nSchrumpf home Saturday.\nMiss Cora Loyning of Red Lodge\nspent the week end at her home\nhere.\nMr. and Mrs. Ed. Hansen and\ndaughter Alene were in Red Lodge\nSaturday.\nMrs. Lucy Wanlesis of Red Lodge\nspent a few days last week at the\nClarence Bjordahl home.\nW. W. Ballard returned the first,\nof the week from Chicago.\nLouie Wiekierak made a business\ntrip to Red Lodge Thursday.\nMr. and Mrs. Henry Wallila vis\nited with relatives on Red Lodge\ncreek Saturday evening.\nMrs. Beatrice Lyn n was a caller\nin Red Lodge Wednesday.\nAbout all the geography they\nneed i n school nowadays is how to\nread a road map.\u2014Ohio State Jour\nnal.\nQuick Relief for\nCoughing Spells\nFAMOUS PRESCRIPTION STOPS\nTHEM ALMOST INSTANTLY\nThe amazing success of this pro\nscription called Thoxine is due to\nits quick double action; it immedi\nately soothes the irritation and\ngoes direct to the internal cause\nnot reached by ordinary medicines.\nThe very first swallow [usually\nstops even the most obstinate co\nugh.\nThoxine is pleasant tasting and\nsafe for the whole family. Your\nmoney will be refunded if it does\nnot give better and quicker relief\nfor coughs and sore throats than\nanything you have ever tried. Put\nup ready for use in 35c, 60c, and\nSpl.00 bottles. Sold by\nECONOMY DRUG COMPANY\ni\u00ae\ni\n\u00ef\n\n\n33*1]\nj\nI\n(Special Correspondence)\nThe Ladies Aid served dinner\n\n1 and su PP er at the hal1 on electlon\n1 a\nH. P. Hanson left on Friday for\nBroadview on business.\nMrs. T. R. Schrumpf entertained\non Saturday in honor of her son\nLouis' seventh birthday. Those pre\nsent were Mrs. S. W. Waples and\nchildren, Mrs. Orr Doty and child\nren of Red Lodge, Mrs. Joe Rooney\nand baby, Mrs. T. C. Schrumpf and\nchildren, Billy, Bobby and Otto\nKebschull, Harold Clark and Da\nvid Burris.\nMr. and Mrs. Dave Anderson of\nJoliet were business callers here\non Tuesday.\nMr. and Mrs. Robert Dullenty\nentertained a number of [friends\nand neighbors at a card party at\ntheir home Friday night. Those\nattending were Mr. and Mrs. T. R.\nSchrumpf, Mr. and Mrs. Chas. Yar\nling, and Mr. and Mrs. W. F. Keb\nschull, and Mi', and Mrs. Joe Roo\nney, and Mrs. Hanson and dau\nghters.\nLida Platt of Joliet was a caller\nin this vicinity on Tuesday.\nMrs. Lula Boyd who has been ill\nfor the past week was taken to the\nDeaconess hospital at Billings on\nFriday.\nMrs. John Hunter and daughter\nand Mrs. Lannie Boyd were Bill\nings callers on Saturday.\nBe\nSiemson and children mo\ntored to Billings on Saturday to\nsee Mrs. Siemson who is ill at the\nhospital there.\n\nMr. and Mrs. W. G. Flood and\nson were callers at Laurel on Sat\nurday.\nC. F. Anderson of Billings visit\ned at the home of relatives here\non Sunday.\nRay Hennebry was a Red Lodge\nbusiness caller on Friday.\nday.\nMrs. John Normile of Joliet was\na caller in this vicinity on Satur\nday.\nMr. a!nd Mrs. Wiryt Anderson\nwere callers at Red Lodge on Fri\nMrs. Ernest Richmond and Jim\nmy left on Friday for a visit with\nrelatives at Ballantine.\nE. P. Decker was a caller at\nRoberts on Monday.\nMrs. C. C. Huddleston spent a\nfew days with relatives at Lau\nrel this past week.\nRobert Dullenty was a business\ncaller at Red Lodge on Thursday.\nMr. and Mrs. J. M. Bresnahan\nand Alice Dullenty spent Sunday\nat the home of relatives here.\nMr. and Mrs. H. P. Hanson were\nbusiness callers at Red Lodge on\nWednesday.\nFlorence Decker who has been\nvisiting at the home of her sister\nat Laurel for a few days arrived\nhome on Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. M. T. Anderson\nand son of Joliet visited at the\nhome of rleatives Sunday.\nMarie Johnson who teaches sch\nool at Laurel spent the week end at\nthe home of her parents.\nMrs. A. G. Anderson left on Sun\nday to visit at the home of her\nson in Rapelje.\nMr. and Mrs. Emmett Taylor\nand children were callers at Red\nLodge on Monday.\nA. G. Anderson attended lodge at\nBillings on Monday evening.\n(Special Correspondence)\nMesdames B. D. Hell and K.\nBlackard motored to the L. C. Gib\nson home Saturday.\nRalph Mellice and family and\nMrs. Elizabeth Fisher of Billings\nwere dinner guests at the L. M.\nHammond home Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. Hersom of Colum\nbus and Mr. and Mrs. C. F. Cham\nberlain of Red Lodge were guests\nat the L. J. Williams home Sunday.\nMesdames Mathwig and Rear\ndon were co-hostesses to the Alter\nSociety Tuesday.\nMiss Katherine Johnson spent\nthe week end at the C. O. Eaton\nhome. Miss Johnson is attending\nthe Johnson's Business College at\nBillings.\nMesdames C. L. and E. F. Bur\nger shopped in Billings Saturday.\nMr. W. D. Fredrick and sons\nGordon and Wendell of Billings\nvisited at the W. R. Fredrick home\n(Special Correspondence)\nMrs. Lillian Halliwill, who has\nbeen in the Adams hospital for the\npast three weeks with a broken\nleg, was able to return to her home\nWednesday.\nMr. and Mrs. Harry Bunn and\nlittle daughter motored to Bill\nings Tuesday.\nMrs. Lambert entertained the\nladies of the Busy Bee Club Thurs\nday. A two course luncheon was\nserved and the afternoon was spent\nin making preparation for a Xmas\nplay and program.\nMrs. J. M. Waters and Miss Ev\nangeline Boggio were shopping in\nColumbus Thursday.\nMrs. Charlie Cortner entertained\nat cards Wednesday evening. Mrs.\nO. Doty was high and Mrs. Jim\nMcKinley low at the two table ses\nsion.\nMrs. Tom Stewart of Roscoe\nspent Friday at the home olf her\ndaughter Mrs. Arthur Higbee.\nG. W. Crawford passed through\nLuther Friday on his way to the\nsawmill in Red Lodge canyon.\nGeo, McCartney and Dave Rus-\nMrs. J. V. Heare and daughter\nRuth, Mrs. Etta Heare, Mrs. Rus\nsell Metcalf and daughter Mildred\nshopped in Red Lodge Saturday.\nMrs. Roth of Laurel is spending\nthe week at the E. C. Russell ran\nch.\n\nsell motored to Red Lodge Satur\nday.\nMiss Audia Tharp and Miss\nFrances Metcalf spent the week\nend at the home of J. J. Metcalf.\nChas. Cortner, Jr. and Arthur\nHigbee motored to Fishtail Satur\nday.\nCharlie Bunn who has been in ehe\nhospital at Billings for the past\nseveral weeks was removed to the\nAdams hospital in Red Lodge Sun\nday.\nJess Rehard, Mrs Maggie Bel\nlamy and Harry Bunn drove to\nBillings Saturday.\nMrs. John Bent, Plyd Kenyen\nand J. M. Waters motored to Fish\ntail Saturday to truck load\na\nof flour.\nQuite a large crowd attended the\ndance at the Tony school house\nSaturday night.\nMrs. W. R. Linley went to Bill\nings Monday to visit a few days\nat the Anderson and Skifstad\nhomes.\nMrs. Harry Obert of Red Lodge\nvisited with relatives at Luther\nSunday.\nMrs. Hoyt Reynolds and child\nren who have been visiting rela\ntives at Fromberg since Wednes\nday returned home Saturday.\nMiss Agnes Secora spent the\nweek end at the home of M. L.\nLong.\nMr. and Mrs. Frank Porath were\nRed Lodge visitors Monday.\nW. R. Linley was an overnight\nvisitor at the home of his daughter,\nMrs. Harry Obert in Red Lodge\nMonday night.\nMrs. Ruth Shaw spent Sunday\nat the home of her uncle and aunt\nMr. and Mrs. Vern Cowger.\nTuesday.\nThe W. R. Hogater family of\nLaurel were guests at the P. G.\nMonahan home Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. Gilbert Egli of\nRed Lodge were guests Sunday at\nthe Fred Egli home.\nMesdames B. D. Bell, Chas. An\nderson and Cora Mendelsshon\nshopped in Billings Friday.\nMrs. E. J. Meyer and Fred Cuno\ntransacted business in Billings\nThursday.\nRoland Gr\u00e4ber of Thermopolis\nvisited the Frank Gr\u00e4ber home the\npast week.\nR. W. Lanter, who has been con\nfined to his home on account of\nsickness is able to be out again.\nMr. and Mrsl iGeorg^ Mullin\nhave moved to the Frank Weiler\nhome for the wintjer while the\nWeilers are in California.\nTo celebrate the anniversary of\nher husband's birthday, Mrs. Geo\nrge Bell entertained at seven o'\nclock dinner Friday evening. Cov\ners were laid for Mr. and Mrs. E.\nW. Talmage and B. D. Hough.\nMrs. Henry Haddox and Mrs.\nBlackard attended the matinee at\nRed Lodge Sunday afternoon.\nSENTS1931 MODEL\nChevrolet's new car for 1931,\npriced substantially below current\nlevels, went o n display last Sat\nurday throughout the nation.\nHeralded as \"The Great Amer\nican Value,\" the new car boasts a\ntwo-inch increase in wheelbase, lar\nger and roomier bodies by Fisher\nwith mohair or broadcloth as op\ntional trimming, and scores of re\nfinements in appearance and per\nformance despite the new prices\nwhich bring the level for the 1931\ncar to a far lower figure than any\nChevrolet, four or six, has ever\nsold.\nDealers throughout the United\nStates put the new models on ex\nhibition Saturday morning for the\nfirst time, nearly two months in\nadvance of the customary date for\nthe showing of the annual new car\nThis move in advancin the annou\nncement date, it was felt by Chev\nrolet officials, would render a dis\ntinct contribution to the cause of\ngeneral business revival by insur\ning extraordinary activity during\ntwo normally dull business months\nnormally\nfor the 200,000 people throughout\nUnited States who depend direct\nly upon Chevrolet for their liveli\nhood.\nThe nineteen domestic produc\ntion plants of the Chevrolet organ\nization are now in full swing on\nthe new models, according to W. S.\nKnudsen, president, and shipments\nare going out to dealers to assure\nimmediate delivery of all models.\nFundamentally the new model\nembodies the same basic features\nwhich, since the introduction of the\nChevrolet Six, enabled it to achieve\na popularity exceeding Chevrolet's\nformer four cylinder model and\nfour times as great as any other\nsix cylinder car. However, scores\nof improvements and refinements\nhave been made this year\u2014every\nchange designed to increase the\nsmartness, performance, saftey or\ndurability of this latest General\nMotors model.\n\nAmong the improvements are a\nfully insulated front compartment,\neasier steering, more durable clu\ntch, and quieter transmission, and\nliberal use of rustless chromium\nplate on exposed bright parts.\nPour Lovejoy hydraulic shock ab\nsorbers, and fully enclosed, weath\nerproof four-wheel brakes contin\nue as standard equipment.\nIn the line of nine body types\nare three open models\u2014the road\nster, phaeton and sport roadster,\nand six closed models\u2014the coach,\n\u25a0sedan, special sedan, the three-win\ndow coupe, the five-window coupe,\nand the isport coupe.\nAll sport models come equipped\nwith new and popular chrome\nplated radiator grille. All models\nhave smart new wire wheels, with\n4.75 by 19 tires, as standard equip\nment. Hubs are very large, of the\nconcealed bolt type, with hub caps\nof gleaming chromium plate set off\nby a black ring circling the Chev\nrolet emblem in the center. Wheel\n\nfinishes harmonize with the wide\nvariety of body combinations.\nHead lamps and tail lamp are\nfull chrome plated in the new\ncar. Chrome plated parking lamps\nattached to the cowl are standard\nequipment with all sport models,\nand the special sedan has front\nfenders with wells for the two\nspare wheels. The models are equ\nipped with one extra wheel to carry\nthe spare in the rear.\nSafety factors stressed in the\nnew car include a frame increased\nfifty per cent in torsional strength,\ncontinuance of the gasoline tank\nin the rear away from the heat of\nthe engine, and the inclusion of a\nflame arrester in the air cleaner.\nThe two-(mch increase in the\nwheelbase has been utilized throu\nghout the line to increase the room\niness and comfort of the new bod\nies. Smart new Duco color com\nbinations, the addition of decor\native body features and a head-on\nappearance extensively changed\nfrom the 1930 car combine to make\nthe 1931 model decidedly finer in\nappearance thn any of its pred\necessors.\nThursday. Mrs. Boyd was later\ntake n to the Deaconess hospital at\nThe radiator has a large cooling\ncapacity this year, and is improv\ned in both efficiency and looks.\nA new treatment of the shell ma\nkes it appear much higher and the\nsides appear to have more curv\nature. At the bottom of the shell\nis a black enameled beaded panel\nsurrounding the starting crank hole\nwhich enters through the radiator\ninstead of the splash pan as form\nerly.\nA chrome-plate tie-bar arches\nfrom fender to fender across the\nfront of the radiator, and holds in\nposition the parabolic chrome-plat\ned head lamps, as well as the new\nand popular high-frequency vibra\ntor horn, which is mounted this\nMary -Monahan was the week\nend guest of Oneita Blaylock.\nMrs. John Normile was a caller\nat the Lulu Boyd home at Boyd\nBillings.\nMr. and Mrs. James Devine have\ntaken ovqr the management of\nthe dining room at MontAqua.\nC. D. Graft motored to Red Lod\nge Saturday evening.\nyear just beneath the left head\nlamp. The splash guard which for\nmerly extended horizontally from\nthe bottom of the radiator\ndrops away vertically in the con\nventional manner.\nFront fenders have been raised\nslightly at the forward end to ach\nieve a lighter and finer appearance,\nand the sweep of the rear fenders\nhas been made more pronounced.\nThe hood is longer, with a high\ner crow n in the upper panels. The\nside hood hinges have been raised\nto coincide with the body molding,\nand this molding is continued\nthrough the hood at the hinge line,\nthe molding being so designed that\nit conceals the hinges. There\nmore hood louvres this year, gr\nouped on a raised panel toward the\nrear of the hood.\nnow\nThe new Fisher bodies all have\na raised line to emphasize the low\nappearance of the car achieved by\nthe deeper side body panels, with\ntheir slight outward bulge. Roof\nAn outstanding feature of the\nnew bodies is the better vision\nmade possible from the driver's\nseat by slightly lowering the seat\nand raising the header bar which\non\nare\nlines are improved by streamlining\nand by an increase in crown at the\nfront,\ntop\nshield. A further aid to clear vision\nfor the driver is the new narrow\nstamped piOar at the ends of the\nwindshield, which arguments the\ni r h P Sr\u00b0Z\u00b0 f the Car A\nAll body mouldings are pressed\nintegral with the body panels, thus\neliminating al separately applied\n\u00c4 Ce Sp Sd\u00c4 t\npressed integral with the roof pan\nels. This method of construction\neliminates the inevitable rust\nstreaks which result when the\nmolding is separately applied be\ncause the paint chips off at the\nconnecting line.\nThe running board is longer and\nnarrower at the front end. The run\nning board aprons follow the con\ntour of the body and appear to be\na continuation of it. Corrugated\nrubber molded in position and ex\ntended over the rounded outside\nedges covers the pressed steel run\nning board, and narrow chrome\nplated molding covers all exposed\nedges.\nAn improved rear end appear\nance is achieved by a newly de\nsigned panel concealing the rear\ncross member and the gas tank.\nThe black enameled panel is set off\nby a large chrome plated filler\ncap on the tank. The combination\nrear lamp-andstop-light is mount\ned on the left fender instead of the\ntire carrier as formerly, and the\nlicense plate is attached to a cross\nbar mounted just below the lamp\nbracket.\nThe interiors of all bodies have\nbeen redesigned to take full advan\ntage of the extra roominess pre\nvidede by the two-inch increase\nin wheelbase. The result is a \"big\ncar\" effect in the interior, just as\nthe added sweep to the exterior\nbody lines creates the impression\nof a considerably larger car than\nlast year.\nSuch fine ear features as assist\nC ord, ash receivers, arm rests and\nsilk roller curtains harmonizing\nwith the interior trimmings may\nbe found in various models in the\nline. All sport models have a lar\nger rear deck to add comfort of\nthe rumble seat passengers. The\ncoach has a compartment for tools\nbeneath the front floor to avoid\ndisturbing the rear seat passen\ngers. All closed models have the\nslanted non-glare windshield, the\nadjustable driver's seat and other\nfeatures which have made Body\nby Fisher the hallmark of quality\nin the fine car field. Mohair or\nbroadcloth trimming is optional\nwith all closed models.\nAll body hardware is newly de\nsigned, narrower and neater in ap\npearance. Chrome plate finishes\nthe exterior hardware and nickel\nplate the interior. All rear doors\nand the left front door are locked\nthis year simply by lifting the door\nhandles instead of by\nsnapping a\nseparate lever.\nThe driver's compartment offers\nextensive changes from last year's\ncar. Instruments are symetrically\n1 grouped on a panel set off by a\nraised head. Control buttons\nblack with with letters and a while\nline rim on their faces. The steer\ning wheel is three-spoke instead of\ntour, affording beter vision of the\ninstrument panel, and the wheel is\nmade of hard rubber molded\nstrong steel frame in the\nolf the costliest cars. The satin\nblack finish of the wheel lends a\nrich appearance to the front\npartment.\nThe new steering mechanism i,=\nof the worm and sector type, with\na reduction ratio of 12 1 instead\nof 9.5 1 as formerly, assuring\neasier and surer control because of\nthe increased ration and new high\ngrade anti-friction bearings.\nAll open and closed bodies have\nautomatic windshield wipers this\nyear, the mechanism so arranged\nthat when the power is shut off the\nblade returns to the extreme pos\nition.\nThe now famous fifty horse\npower va!ve-in-head six cylinder en\ngine which Chevrolet introduced in\n1928 is retained in the new car in\nall its fundamentals, although it\nhas been refined for greated rigid\nity, smoothness and durability.\nRibs added to the cylinder block\nachieve a 43 per cent increase in\nrigidity with only a one and one\nhalf percent increase in weight.\nire\non a\nmanner\ncom\nThe strength of the crankshaft\nhas been increased by the addition\nof metal in the short arms, which\nresults in greater engine smooth\nness. The harmonic balancer, in\ntroduced during the 1930 season,\nhas been simplified in design for\nthe more effective dampening out\nof vibration at the critical speed of\nthe crankshaft,\nDuring the 1930\nseason a ring\ngear of high carbon steel was for\nthe first time securely welded to\nthe flywheel. This method of\nstruction is continued in the new\ncar, and minimizes the possibility\nof broken flywheel teeth and\nmeans better and easier engage\nment of the started pinion.\n_.\nimprovements in the en\nhousW wHbtb ^designed clutch\nto f e closure at the hot\nou g th f ee se P ar\nnr y fn> 1 e Pieces instead of\ne easiei access foi ad -1\nnin and LgSiv^spaTk^'l^J\na new rubber boot over the car\njburetor accelerator pump to exclude\n1 the pUmp ^'iderami\na nlw leak nZf l Weath r;\nL JnSS lL T\"'\nsure f t g f e \"reater pres\ncylim J. P alls to\ncon\nf e Ctivp X\ndes igned valve push rods \"with\nthe spherical socket made integ\nral with the rod to eliminate tbe\nextra joint with its consequent\nP\u00b0 ssibilit y of wear and noise;\nimproved water pum (for ater\ndurability, valve springs of\nable pitchj asuring P ti J ht closure\nf Va,VeS and\nan\nvan\nspring\nvibration; a copper mesh air clean\ner and flame arrested instead of\na centrifugal cleaner; and\ntype crankcase ventilator, combin\ned with the oil filler and provided\nwith an oil separator, which drains\noff engine fumes through the\nderpan instead of through the\nburetor as formerly.\na new\nun\ncar\nRefinements in design contribute\nmaterially to smoother operation\nand longer life of the clutch. Mold\ned clutch facings replace the\nen type; the clutch pilot bearing is\nnow ball bearing instead of bronze\nbushing, and a spherical pivot\nplaces the yoke bracket and pin at\nthe clutch for mounting.\nThe transmission case has been\nchanged to secure greater rigidity\nand to permit access without e-,\ninoval of the clutch housing. T\nuse of nickel-molybdenum alloy\nsteel in the second speed counter\nshaft and sliding gears, carbonized\nto produce a very hard surface as\nsures maximum life and minimizes\nwear and breakage possibilities,\nwov\nre.\nWith the lengthening of the\nwheelbase to 109 inches, more than\nat\n4\nv' Y\noies by Explorer\nd\ny?.\nI\nm\na\n\\f\noi\nW/\n\n/\u00df\n\nI\n\n\n$1\n.4\u00bb\n\n\nK\n\n7//.\ntom'A\n\ny'\nafe'\n\n\n\nI ipp\nM\u00c2T\nm\n\n\n\nPi\nll\n\nV:\n\u25a0tUJm\nV\n\n\nv\n\n\nm\nK\nm\n\nm\n\u25a0V\nEft\nI\net\n\u00bbp:,\nPM\n\nj\nm\n0\n\nmi\ni mm\nj\u00bb, a 4\nI I\nII*\ni W\ni \u00e6mm\n\u2022iM\n\u00fc I\n,v\nHI CHARD KoNTEPu\nr fTflfp rh \\l\u00dfr f\n\n\u00a3~nr *~i\nl 4\ntd\ntown in Al-kkirn-AwWnhu tries\u00bb'W-\u00ffnih \u00e4ijk, S<tivuh sjjt-ly\n\u25a0Iva just Wit i w\u00ab!<i) lul-l.vty\nnwr\nFamous Musician Takes\nHawaiian Instrument\non Polar Tours\nNew York City.\u2014Dick Konter\nhas played music farther north\nand south than any other human\nbeing. He accompanied the Byrd\nexpeditions to the North and South\npoles and was within seven hun\ndred fifty miles of the northern\nand southern extremities of the\nearth. Accompanying him was his\nukelele!\n\"American dance music is the\nonly music with universal appeal,\"\nsays Konter. \"Neither the Es\nquimaux nor the Maoris got any\nthing out of high class music. It\nwas only when we played syncopa\ntion that they became interested in\nthe ukulele.\"\ntwo inches longer than last\nthe frame has been redesigned,\nwith increased metal applied at\nadvantageous points to effect great\nsafety and rigidity. Side rails of\nthe frame have been increased\nsection. Front and rear cross\nbers and the rear engine support\nall have been changed to reduce\u00bb\nstress and provide greater rigidity\nand safety. A sturdy stamped\nbracket extends outward from lht>\nframe to support the body more ef\nfectively, and reduce frame stesses\nand body deflections.\nyear.\nm\nmem\n\n,T changes extend the\nstep hanRer tle bar the exhaust\nsystem, improved spring construc\nturn both front and rear, improved\nand redesigned self-adjusting spr\ninff shackles, a strengthened front\naxle and a lengthened third mem\nher of the rear axle to complement\nthe increase j n wheel base and ra\ndesigned rear spring seats with U\nb ltS m erSed S that the b ltS\nstraddle the spring and set para\nllel to the axle housing. This last\nmentioned change eliminates rat\ntles due to excessive wear. A new\nmethod of lubricating the\nseats also retards wear and\nvents rattles.\nspring\npre\nThe culminative effect of the\nimprovements in the new model,\nwhich extend to every fundamental\npart of the chassis or body, mean\na safer, longer lasting, better per\nforming, and very much smarter\nappearing ear. This factor, coupled\nwith the reduced\nprices, [repre\nsents a product which promises to\nprove one of the most popular cars\nin the history of the company.\nEvery change and new feature\nhas met and survived innumerable\ntests befoi'e being incorporated in\nthe 1931 car. Consistent with the\nestablished policy of \"working two\nyears ahead,\" the Chrevrolet engi\nneering department was at work\non this new car befor the public\nshowing of last year's model. Each\none of the twenty major engineers\nhas been at work on various units,\noftentimes two\n\niindustry, and in the large corps of\nexpert craftsmen of the Fisher\nBody organization. The combined\nias K>en brought to bear on the\nnew 1931 Chevrolet that it might\nor more engineers\nworking independently on the same\nunit.\nEntirely apart fi'om Chevrolet's\nown engineers and designers there\nwere further facilities for the de\nvelopment of the car in the Gener\nal Motors Laboratories, the most\nextensive project of its kind in the\ntalent of these vast organizations\nmeasure up to its slogan of \"The\nGreat American Value.\"\nKonter taught a class of Maori\ngirls in the southernmost part of\nNew Zealand and also had a\nof Esquimaux girls beyond\nArctic Circle. \"Try as I might, I\ncould not get them interested in\nanything but rhythm,\" he ex\nplains. \"They all like dreamy\nsouthern songs of the mammy\nvariety, though I was surprised\nto hoar the Maoris singing the\n'Stein Song.'\n'Alabama Lullaby,' a mammy\nwaltz song which a friend sent\nalso made a great hit in the Ant\narctic. It was quite a sight to\nhundreds of Maoris dancing to this\nas\n\u25a0e\npleasant piece,\nwho made both poles with Byrd,\nHe is an ex-navy man and bet\npolar jaunts teaches ukelele which\nhe learned first-hand in the Ha\nwaiian Islands.\n\ns\nKonter is one of the few\nmen","height":"21453","width":"15585"}}
